    <div class="text-block">
        <h2>Establishing the Main User Flow</h2>
        <p>With the primary user narrative created, I then moved on to creating/concepting the main user flow. A requirement set forth by the client was when Bob was to send out a distributed marketing message, the experience was to be similar to a wizard. They wanted the platform to guide the user as much as possible from step to step. My initial flow followed the initial information given by client:
            <ul>
                <li>New Campaign → Select Template → Edit template → Preview edits → Test send campaign → Select Segment/Audience → Schedule campaign delivery</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Image Block -->
    <div>
        <img class="shadow" src="/images/designmap/userflow-1.png">
    </div>

    <div class="text-block">
        <p>The main issue / question that came to mind was: <strong>Why would you force Bob to select an audience before choosing a template?</strong> Bob is not a marketer, he may not know exactly who he wants to target. By allowing him to select a template first, it could act as inspiration, allowing him to achieve his goal(s) more efficiently.</p>

        <p>My feedback was met with a little resistance and the client was adamant about giving the user the option of selecting a segment first. The flow was then adjusted to reflect a suitable compromise:
            <ul>
                <li>New Campaign → Option to select a template or segment first → edit template → preview edits → test send campaign → Schedule campaign</li>
            </ul>
        By giving Bob the option to select a template or segment first, I was able to still provide an exploratory experience. </p>
    </div>

